<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Twenty-sixth session 
</b>Agenda item 3 
<b>Promotion and protection of all human rights, civil, 
political, economic, social and cultural rights, 
including the right to development 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Report of the Working Group on the issue of human rights 
and transnational corporations and other business 
enterprises 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Addendum 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Report on the First Latin America and Caribbean Regional Forum on 
Business and Human Rights</b>* 
</p>
<p> <i>Summary</i> 
 In November 2012 the Working Group decided that to increase the number of 
persons, victims, civil society actors, businesses, Governments and regional organizations 
actively involved in the uptake of the Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights, 
Regional Forums would be made an integral part of its working methods. The purpose of 
these regional gatherings is to identify challenges and best practices and to spur the creation 
of local networks and capabilities and of forums for dialogue that bring together civil 
society, Governments and businesses so that they may discover common foundations that 
will make progress on the uptake of the Guiding Principles possible. The aim of the 
Regional Forums, moreover, is to encourage local uptake of the Guiding Principles by 
putting the issue on the agendas of economic and political actors. The Guiding Principles 
may well be a universal set of guidelines, but implementing them in a particular case 
requires meeting local needs. 
</p>
<p> This report covers the major themes and the points of view expressed by participants 
in the First Latin America and Caribbean Regional Forum on Business and Human Rights, 
</p>
<p>  
</p>
<p><b> </b>* The summary of the present report is being circulated in all official languages. The report itself, 
contained in the annex to the summary, is being circulated in the language of submission only. 
</p>
<p> United Nations A/HRC/26/25/Add.2
</p>
<p> 
</p>
